1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. Be3 exd4
{ A surprise for my opponent! In all previous games I had played in the Gligoric System, I had gone  7...Ng4  . }
8. Nxd4 Re8 9. f3 c6 10. Bf2 d5 11. exd5 cxd5 12. O-O
{ 12.c5  Nc6  13.O-O  Nh5  14.Qd2  Be5  15.g3  Ng7!  16.Rfd1  Bf5  Black should be fine as in Sarana-Grischuk, World Rapid 2019.  The game Kasparov-Carlsen, Reykjavik instead went @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp3p1p/2n3p1/2Ppb2n/3N4/2N2PP1/PP1QBB1P/R4RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bh3?!  16.Rfe1  Ng7  17.Rad1±  . }
12... Nc6 13. Nxc6
{ The first sign that my surprise in the opening has worked out. I had noticed that my opponent, being primarily a 1.e4 player, had limited experience in this line and he clearly was not prepared for 7...exd4 as I had never played it before.   13.c5  transposes back into the lines above featuring 12.c5. }
13... bxc6 14. Rc1
{ A strange move. After  14.cxd5  Nxd5  15.Nxd5  cxd5  16.Rc1  Qd6  Black is slightly better, but the advantage is hardly decisive. }
14... Bh6 15. Rb1 Bf5 16. Bd3 d4 17. Bxf5
{ Or  17.Ne2  Bxd3  18.Qxd3  Be3  19.Rbd1  Bxf2+  20.Rxf2  c5  21.b4=  . }
17... dxc3 18. Bd3 cxb2 19. Rxb2 Be3
{ An important exchange of bishops as White loses the bishop pair but also the black knight on f6 is infinitely better than the bad bishop on d3. }
20. Bxe3 Rxe3 21. Be2 Qe7 22. Rf2 Re8 23. g3 h5 24. Qd4 Rd8 25. Qf4 Kg7 26. Kg2
h4
{ Maybe not objectively the best, but it forces a very unpleasant endgame where White will suffer.   26...a5  27.Bf1  a4  is also very good for Black but it is way less forcing. }
27. Qxh4 Qe5 28. Qf4
{ Not  28.Bf1  g5  29.Qh3  Rh8  and the queen is trapped. } 28... Qxf4 29. gxf4
Nh5 30. Bf1 Nxf4+ 31. Kg3 Nh5+ 32. Kg2 Rd1
{ Black has all the trumps here. More active rooks and a dominant knight as well as a much safer king. }
33. Rb3 Ree1 34. f4 f5 { Fixing the weakness on f4. } 35. Bd3 Kh6 36. Kf3 c5
37. Ra3 a6 38. Rb2 Re6 39. Rb8 Rde1 40. Rh8+ Kg7 41. Rd8 R1e3+ 42. Kf2 Nxf4
{ After the f4-pawn finally falls, the rest is elementary. } 43. Rb3 Rh3 44.
Bf1 Rxh2+ 45. Kg3 Rh1 46. Rd1 Nh5+ 47. Kg2 Rh4 48. Rd7+ Kh6 49. Rc7 Rg4+ 50.
Kf2 Nf6 51. Bd3 Rf4+ 52. Kg3 Kg5 53. Rxc5 Re3+ 54. Kg2 Ng4
{ 55.Rb2  Rxd3   55.Rd5  Rf2+  56.Kg1  Re1+  57.Bf1  Rexf1  . } *

