1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. f4
{ A very unusual setup by White. It is extremely rare to put the bishop on g5 and then follow up with the four pawns setup. }
6... c5
{ In almost all King's Indians it is important to strike at the center with either c5 or e5. Seeing that e5 is almost impossible here, c5 makes a lot of sense.   6...e5?  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.fxe5+-  simply loses a piece. }
7. d5 b5
{ A very enterprising sacrifice. Surprisingly enough, the computer thinks that this is completely sound as White is lacking any development on the kingside. While the pieces are placed differently, this is reminiscent of another game @@StartBracket@@0-1 Svidler-Nakamura, Rhodes 2013@@EndBracket@@.   7...e6?  is a mistake due to  8.e5+-  . }
8. cxb5
{ 8.Nxb5?  Nxe4-+  loses almost immediately as Black has too many threats. }
8... a6 9. bxa6
{ White completely neglects his development here and tries to grab the 'extra' pawn on a6. This is simply too slow!   9.Nf3  was definitely better and after  9...axb5  White should play  10.Bxf6  , but let's examine another move first:  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1ppP2B1/4PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bxb5  Nxe4!  @@StartBracket@@a thematic idea that all Benoni/Benko players are familiar with!@@EndBracket@@ and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxe4  Qa5+  12.Nc3  Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Qxb5  @@StartBracket@@it's important to note that we are preventing White from castling@@EndBracket@@  14.Kf2  f6  15.Bh6  Re8  16.Re1  Qb2+  17.Qd2  Qxd2+  18.Nxd2  Nd7  and White is completely losing in this endgame due to the bad placement of the bishop on h6 combined with the weak pawns on a2, c3 and d5. Black can easily develop via ...Nb6 threatening d5, and ...Ba6 which gains control of the important c4-square.  After  19.a4  Nb6  20.a5  Nxd5-+  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/3np2p/3p1ppB/2pP4/5P2/2P5/P2N1KPP/R3R3 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.c4  Ra4  20.a3  Nb6  21.Rac1  Rxa3-+  Black is winning.  B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p2p1/1BpP2B1/4nP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.O-O  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxc3  wins an easy pawn. We will retreat via ...Bf6 to protect our e7-pawn.   Let's go back to the right continuation for White after 9...axb5: @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1ppP2B1/4PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Bxb5  .  Now Black has two options:  A@@EndBracket@@  11...Bxc3+  12.bxc3  Qa5  13.Qd3  Ba6  @@StartBracket@@a developing move with a beneficial trade@@EndBracket@@  14.Bxa6  Qxa6  15.c4  @@StartBracket@@if @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/4pp1p/q2p2p1/2pP4/4PP2/2PQ1N2/P5PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Qxa6  then  15...Rxa6  followed by ...Nd7, ...Rfa8 and Black is more than comfortable  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/4pp1p/q2p2p1/2pP4/2P1PP2/3Q1N2/P5PP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qa3  16.Qe2  Nd7  17.e5  Rfb8  and we reached another position where Black should be fine, but it is not exactly what one aims for when they play the King's Indian.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4pp1p/3p1bp1/1BpP4/4PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ba6  is also possible  12.a4  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4pp1p/3p2p1/1BpP4/4PP2/2b2N2/PP4PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e5  Bg7  13.Bxa6  Nxa6  14.O-O  c4  15.Qe2  Nb4=∞  it would appear that Black has enough compensation for the pawn, although it should be easier for White to play  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/4pp1p/b2p1bp1/1BpP4/P3PP2/2N2N2/1P4PP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qa5  13.O-O  Bxc3  14.bxc3  Qxc3  15.Qd2  Qxd2  16.Nxd2=  and the position is equal, but White is to be preferred. }
9... Bxa6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Nf3 Qb6 12. Rb1
{ The position is already very bad for White, but after this move there is no coming back. }
12... c4 13. Qe2 Rfc8
{ 13...Nb4!  Was much better. Let's examine a few of White's options:   A@@EndBracket@@  14.Kf1  Nxa2-+  White has no coordination.  B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/1q1p1np1/3P2B1/1np1PP2/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R w K - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nd2  Nd3+  15.Kf1  Qd4  16.Nf3  Qa7-+  With tremendous attacking potential. Black is completely winning.   C.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/1q1p1np1/3P2B1/1np1PP2/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R w K - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qxc4  I suspect that I rejected Nb4 at the time because of this natural looking capture, but Black even has more than one move here. He shouldn't play  14...Qe3+?  15.Qe2  Nd3+  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/3P2B1/1n2PP2/2N1qN2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R b K - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nc2+  16.Kf1+-  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/3P2B1/4PP2/2NnqN2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R w K - 3 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Kf1+-  but the following two moves are both fine.  C.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/1q1p1np1/3P2B1/1nQ1PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/1R2K2R b K - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nc2+  15.Kd2  Rfc8  16.Qe2  Ng4-+  Black is winning but this is a very hard move to find.   C.3@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4ppbp/1q1p1np1/3P2B1/1nQ1PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/1R2K2R b K - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Ng4!  15.Qe2  Rfc8  16.e5  @@StartBracket@@if @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4ppbp/1q1p2p1/3P2B1/1n2PPn1/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R w K - 3 16@@EndFEN@@  16.h3  then  16...Ne3-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4ppbp/1q1p2p1/3PP1B1/1n3Pn1/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R b K - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Ne3-+  The knights are too powerful. }
14. Qf2
{ 14.Bxf6  was the better choice:   A@@EndBracket@@  14...Bxf6  15.e5  dxe5  16.fxe5  Bg7  17.Qf2  Qxf2+  18.Kxf2  Nb4  19.Rhd1  Nxa2  20.Ne4  Nb4=  or @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4pp1p/nq1p1bp1/3PP3/2p2P2/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R b K - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bg7  16.Qf2=  and White cannot claim any advantage, but he is no longer losing.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4ppbp/nq1p1Bp1/3P4/2p1PP2/2N2N2/PP2Q1PP/1R2K2R b K - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...exf6  15.Qf2  Nc5  16.O-O  Rab8=  Both sides have play here. Black is preferred. }
14... Nc5 15. O-O Ng4
{ I recall that GM Bisguier simply forgot that I had this move and it ends the game at once. If it was any consolation, the position is simply lost anyway. }
16. Qe2 Nxe4+ 17. Kh1 Ngf2+ 18. Kg1 Nh3+ 19. Kh1 Nef2+
{ Unfortunately, the attempt at a smothered mate simply doesn't work here:  19...Qg1+??  20.Nxg1  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4ppbp/3p2p1/3P2B1/2p1nP2/2N2N1n/PP2Q1PP/1R3RqK w - - 6 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Rxg1  Nhf2+  21.Qxf2  Nxf2  there's the smothered mate  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/4ppbp/3p2p1/3P2B1/2p1nP2/2N4n/PP2Q1PP/1R3RNK b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nhf2+  21.Rxf2  Nxf2+  22.Qxf2+-  . }
20. Rxf2 Nxf2+ 21. Kg1 Ne4+
{ White is simply down too much material to continue. If  22.Kh1  then  Nxc3+-  . }
