1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. f3 f5 11. Be3
{ The other way for White to play after 9.Ne1 is developing the bishop to d2:  11.Nd3  f4  12.Bd2  g5  13.Rc1  Ng6  14.c5  Nf6  15.Nb5  Rf7  16.Ba5  b6  17.cxd6  cxd6  18.Be1  g4  19.fxg4  Nxe4  20.Nb4  a6  21.Bf3  Ng3  22.Nxd6  Qxd6  23.Rc6  Qf8  24.hxg3  fxg3  25.d6  e4  26.Be2  Rxf1+  27.Bxf1  Bxg4  28.Qd5+  Kh8  29.Rc7  Be6  30.Qxe4  Bf5  31.Qd5  Be4  32.Qd2  Be5  33.Rc4  Bb7  34.d7  Rd8  35.Nc6  Bxc6  36.Rxc6  Qf5  37.Rc8  Rxc8  38.Qd3  Qf8  39.dxc8=Q  Qxc8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Ragger,M @@StartBracket@@2689@@EndBracket@@ -Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2787@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2016. }
11... f4 12. Bf2 g5 { White has tried many moves here. } 13. Nd3
{ For  13.Rc1  see theKasimdzhanov game.   13.a4  was played in  0-1 @@StartBracket@@16@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2704@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@ Cap d'Agde 2008.   13.g4!?  h5  14.h3  Rf6  15.Nd3  Rh6  16.Kg2  c5  17.dxc6  Nxc6  18.c5  dxc5  19.Nxc5  Nd4  20.Bc4+  Kh7  21.Nb3  Nf6?  22.Nxd4  exd4  23.e5  hxg4  24.hxg4  Nxg4  25.fxg4  Bxe5  26.Rh1  1-0 @@StartBracket@@93@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2754@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2774@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2011 CBM. }
13... Ng6 14. c5 Nf6 15. Rc1 Rf7 16. Kh1 h5 17. cxd6
{ By far the most common move order. It's very likely Wesley simply mixed up the move order in the game. In most of these lines Black will sacrifice a7 for time to play g4-g3. Let's see what can happen after  17.Nb5  :   A@@EndBracket@@  17...a6  18.Na3  @@StartBracket@@with the white pawn still on c5, Black isn't able to lock away the knight with b5 as in the game@@EndBracket@@  18...Bf8  19.cxd6  @@StartBracket@@something like this is possibly what Wesley had in mind@@EndBracket@@  19...Bxd6  20.Nc4  g4  21.Nc5   B.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/ppp2rb1/3p1nn1/1NPPp1pp/4Pp2/3N1P2/PP2BBPP/2RQ1R1K b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...g4!  18.cxd6  cxd6  19.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@an attempt to disallow the Nxe4 trick, but giving up even more time@@EndBracket@@  19...g3?  @@StartBracket@@Black should avoid this move@@EndBracket@@  20.Nc7  Rxc7  21.Qxc7  Qxc7  22.Rxc7  gxf2  23.Rfc1  Bd7  24.Rxb7  Bc8  25.Rbc7  Bd7  26.Nxf2±  like in 1-0  Shirov, A-Bacrot,E, Bilbao 2014 CBM@@EndBracket@@.   B.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/pp3rb1/3p1nn1/1N1Pp2p/4Ppp1/3N1P2/PPQ1BBPP/2R2R1K b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Ne8  20.Nxa7  Bd7  21.Qb3  g3  22.Bg1  Bf8  23.Rfd1  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r2qnbk1/Np1b1r2/3p2n1/3Pp2p/4Pp2/1Q1N1Pp1/PP2B1PP/2R2RBK w - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Ne1  gxh2  24.Bb6  Qg5  25.Bb5  h4  26.Bxd7  Rxd7  27.Nb5  Nf6  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2qnbk1/Np1b1r2/3p2n1/3Pp2p/4Pp2/1Q1N1Pp1/PP2B1PP/2RR2BK b - - 3 23@@EndFEN@@  23...gxh2  24.Bf2  h4  @@StartBracket@@even stronger is @@StartFEN@@r2qnbk1/Np1b1r2/3p2n1/3Pp2p/4Pp2/1Q1N1P2/PP2BBPp/2RR3K b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rg7  25.Kxh2  Nh4  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2qnbk1/Np1b1r2/3p2n1/3Pp3/4Pp1p/1Q1N1P2/PP2BBPp/2RR3K w - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Kxh2  Qg5  26.Qxb7  h3  27.g4  fxg3+  28.Bxg3  Qe3  29.Qxa8  Qxe2+  30.Nf2  Rxf3  31.Rf1  Rxg3  0-1 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Kjartansson,G @@StartBracket@@2468@@EndBracket@@-Kavutskiy, K @@StartBracket@@2347@@EndBracket@@ Reykjavik 2017.   B.3@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/pp3rb1/3p1nn1/1N1Pp2p/4Ppp1/3N1P2/PP2BBPP/2RQ1R1K w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Nxa7  has been well explored both over the board and in correspondence. As long as black knows a few lines after 20...Nxe4, fxe4 and f3, he can't be worse, and White is usually the one who should be careful:  19...Bd7  20.Qb3  Nxe4!  21.fxe4  f3  22.gxf3  gxf3  23.Bb6  fxe2  24.Rxf7  Qh4  25.Rf3  Qxe4  26.Ne1  Bg4  27.h3  Nf4  28.hxg4  hxg4  29.Rc8+  Rxc8  30.Nxc8  gxf3  31.Qxf3  Qh7+  32.Kg1  Nh3+  33.Kg2  Nf4+  34.Kf2  Qh4+  35.Qg3  Nh3+  36.Kg2  Nf4+=   B.4@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2q2k1/Np1b1rb1/3p2n1/3Pp2p/4P1p1/1Q1N1p2/PP2BBPP/2R2R1K w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Bb6  Qh4  23.Bxf3  gxf3  24.Rxf3  Rxf3  25.gxf3  Rf8  . }
17... cxd6 18. Nb5 a6 19. Na3
{ 19.Nc3  is a possible try to justify White's move order mishap, trying to exploit the b6-square, but it's very hard to believe White can play so slowly:  19...g4  20.Na4  g3  21.Nb6  Rb8  22.Bg1  gxh2  23.Bf2  Bd7  24.Nxd7  Nxd7  25.Qe1  Bf6  . }
19... b5 20. Rc6
{ Planting the knight on c6 with  20.Nb4  has been tried as well, but it's not actually doing very much, and Black's attack is unimpeded:  20...g4  21.Nc6  Qf8  22.Bb6  Bd7  23.Rc3  Bh6  24.Nc2  Rg7  .   The computer suggests  20.Nc2  20...g4  21.Ncb4  as the only way for White not to lose. For a human it's hard to go for this over the immediate Nb4-c6. }
20... g4 21. Qc2 Qf8
{ 21...Bf8!  was even stronger:  22.Rc1  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/5r2/p1Rp1nn1/1p1Pp2p/4Ppp1/N2N1P2/PPQ1BBPP/5R1K w - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Bb6  Qe8  23.Rc7  Bd7  24.Rc1  Rg7∓  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/5r2/p1Rp1nn1/1p1Pp2p/4Ppp1/N2N1P2/PPQ1BBPP/2R4K b - - 3 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Bd7  23.Rc7  g3  24.Bg1  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r2q1bk1/2Rb1r2/p2p1nn1/1p1Pp2p/4Pp2/N2N1Pp1/PPQ1BBPP/2R4K w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Bb6  Qb8  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2q1bk1/2Rb1r2/p2p1nn1/1p1Pp2p/4Pp2/N2N1Pp1/PPQ1B1PP/2R3BK b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...gxh2  25.Bf2  h4-+  .   Also good is  21...g3  22.Bb6  Qf8  23.Rc1  Bd7  . }
22. Rc1 Bd7 23. Rc7
{ The hanging exchange was the least of White's problems.   23.Nb4  is probably the best try, but Black is still doing great with accurate play:  23...g3!  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp1nn1/1p1Pp2p/1N2Ppp1/N4P2/PPQ1BBPP/2R4K b - - 5 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Bxc6?!  24.dxc6=∞  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp1nn1/1p1Pp2p/1N2Pp2/N4Pp1/PPQ1BBPP/2R4K w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Bg1  gxh2  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  25.Bxh2  Ng4!  26.fxg4  hxg4   A.1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp2n1/1p1Pp2p/1N2Ppn1/N4P2/PPQ1B1PB/2R4K w - - 1 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Nxa6  Qd8  27.Nxb5  Qh4  28.fxg4  hxg4  29.Bxg4  Bxg4  30.Nxd6  Ne7  31.Nxf7  Kxf7  32.Kg1  Rh8  33.g3  Qh5   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp1nn1/1p1Pp2p/1N2Pp2/N4P2/PPQ1B1Pp/2R3BK w - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Bf2  Nxe4!  26.fxe4  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp2n1/1p1Pp2p/1N2np2/N4P2/PPQ1BBPp/2R4K w - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Bd3  Nxf2+  27.Qxf2  Ne7  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4qk1/3b1rb1/p1Rp2n1/1p1Pp2p/1N2Pp2/N7/PPQ1BBPp/2R4K b - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26...f3  27.gxf3  Bh6  . }
23... Bh6 24. Be1 { Stepping away from g4-g3. } 24... h4 25. fxg4
{ Overlooking Black's next move. } 25... f3 26. gxf3 Nxe4 27. Rd1
{ 27.fxe4  Rf1+  28.Kg2  Be3!  is curtains due to  29.Bxf1  h3+  .   The machine suggests:  27.Nf2  Nxf2+  28.Bxf2  Bxc1  29.Qxg6+  Rg7  30.Qe4  Qf4  31.Qxf4  Bxf4  with a hopeless endgame for White. }
27... Rxf3 28. Rxd7
{ Or  28.Bxf3  Qxf3+  29.Qg2  Qxg2+  30.Kxg2  Bxg4  31.Rb1  h3+  32.Kg1  Rf8-+  . }
28... Rf1+ 29. Kg2 Be3
{ 29...h3+  was the most beautiful finish:  30.Kxh3  Rf2  31.Bxf2  Qxf2  32.Nxf2  Nf4+  33.Kh4  Bg5  . }
30. Bg3 hxg3 31. Rxf1 Nh4+ 32. Kh3 Qh6 33. g5 Nxg5+ 34. Kg4 Nhf3 35. Nf2 Qh4+
