{ It's possible to offer the trade immediately with  17...Bf8  , before White makes room on g1. Play slows down a bit, but it's still quite interesting:  18.Bxf8  Qxf8  19.Rc1  Kh8!?  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b2qk1/ppp2r1p/5nn1/1P1Pp1p1/P1N1Pp2/2N2P2/4B1PP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...h5  20.Qb3  g4  21.b6  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b2q1k/ppp2r1p/5nn1/1P1Pp1p1/P1N1Pp2/2N2P2/4B1PP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Kh1  Nh5  21.Kg1  Ng3  22.Rf2  . }
18. a5 { Or  18.d6  Be6  19.Nd5  cxd6  20.Nxd6  Bf8!  . } 18... g4 19. b6
{ 19.Bf2  is too slow. Black will happily sac the pawn on g3 followed by h5-h4, clearing the h5- and f4-squares for the black knights:  19...Bf8  20.b6  axb6  21.axb6  Rxa1  22.Qxa1  g3  23.hxg3  fxg3  24.Bxg3  h4  25.Bf2  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1P3nn1/3Pp3/2N1P2p/2N2PB1/4B1P1/Q4RK1 w - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Bh2  Bc5+  26.Kh1  Nh5-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1P3nn1/3Pp3/2N1P2p/2N2P2/4BBP1/Q4RK1 b - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Nf4  26.Nxe5  N6h5  27.Nxf7  Kxf7-+  . }
19... g3
{ The race is on! Black is completely lost on the queenside, but on the other hand, White is nearly mated. }
20. Kh1
{ This very typical maneuver Kh1+Bg1 is also often seen in the Mar del Plata. }
20... Bf8
{ It's also possible to include  20...axb6  first:  21.axb6  Rxa1  22.Qxa1  Bf8  23.Bg1  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1P3nn1/2BPp2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/Q4R1K w - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23.bxc7  Rxc7  24.Bg1  Bh3!  25.gxh3  Qc8  26.Rc1  Nh4  27.Bf1  Rxc4  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1P3nn1/3Pp2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/Q4RBK b - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23...gxh2  24.Bf2  h4  25.Nb5  h3  26.g4  fxg3  27.Bxg3  Nh5  28.Bxh2  Bc5  29.bxc7  Qh4  30.Qe1!  Qf6  31.f4  exf4  32.Bxh5  Qg5  33.Qe2  f3  34.Bxf3  Nh4  35.Qd2  Qg7  36.Qb2  as in 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Sospedra Sebastian, J @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@-Nekhaev, A @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016.   Another serious attempt is  20...Nh7!?  21.d6  Qh4  22.Bg1  Ng5  Black's focus can shift entirely to the white bishop on g1, so the knight is looking to land on h3, and the dark-squared bishop would love to get to c5.   Instead, the attempt to win immediately by brute force with  22...Bh3  doesn't quite work due to  23.gxh3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r5k1/ppp2rbn/1P1P2n1/P3p2p/2N1Pp1q/2N2Ppb/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 3 23@@EndFEN@@  23.bxc7  Bxg2+  24.Kxg2  Qh3+  25.Kxh3  Ng5+  26.Kg2  Nh4+  0-1 Ftacnik,L @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@-Cvitan,O @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1997 CBM@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r5k1/ppp2rbn/1P1P2n1/P3p2p/2N1Pp1q/2N2PpP/4B2P/R2Q1RBK b - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Qxh3  24.Rf2+-   After 22...Ng5 White has the following options:  A@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/ppp2rb1/1P1P2n1/P3p1np/2N1Pp1q/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 3 23@@EndFEN@@  23.dxc7  Bf8  24.Nd6  Nh3!  25.gxh3  Bxh3  26.Rf2  gxf2  27.Nxf7  Kxf7  28.Qd5+  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r4b2/ppP2k2/1P4n1/P3p2p/4Pp1q/2N2P1b/4Bp1P/R2Q2BK w - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Bxf2  Qxf2  29.Bf1  Be6∓  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4b2/ppP2k2/1P4n1/P2Qp2p/4Pp1q/2N2P1b/4Bp1P/R5BK b - - 1 28@@EndFEN@@  28...Kg7  29.Bxf2  Qxf2  30.Rg1  Kh6  31.Qf7  Nh4  32.Qf6+  Kh7=   B.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/ppp2rb1/1P1P2n1/P3p1np/2N1Pp1q/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 3 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Ra2  axb6  24.dxc7  Bf8  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/1pP2rb1/1p4n1/P3p1np/2N1Pp1q/2N2Pp1/R3B1PP/3Q1RBK b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Kh7  25.Nb5  Be6  26.Nbd6  Nh3!  27.gxh3  Qxh3  28.Bd3  Rxc7  and @@StartFEN@@r7/1pP2rbk/1p2b1n1/PN2p1np/2N1Pp1q/5Pp1/R3B1PP/3Q1RBK w - - 3 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Qd8  Rc8!  27.Nbd6  Bf6  28.Nf5  Bxd8  29.cxd8=Q  Rxf5  @@EndBracket@@  B.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/1pP2rb1/1p4n1/P3p1np/2N1Pp1q/2N2Pp1/R3B1PP/3Q1RBK b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Bf8  25.Qd8  Rxc7  26.Qxc7  Bc5  27.Ne3  Bxe3  28.Bc4+  Kh8  29.Rd1  Bg4∞  . }
21. d6
{ Or  21.Bg1  and now:  A.1@@EndBracket@@  21...Nh4  22.Re1?  @@StartBracket@@this game between Roussel Roozmon and Charbonneau was major inspiration behind playing these Ne8 lines in the first place@@EndBracket@@  22...Nxg2  23.Kxg2  Rg7  24.Nxe5  gxh2+  25.Kh1  Nxe4  0-1 Roussel Roozmon,T - Charbonneau, P, Montreal 2008.   A.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/ppp2r2/1P3n2/P2Pp2p/2N1Pp1n/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 4 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Ra2!?  Bh3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/ppp2r2/1P3n2/P2Pp2p/2N1Pp1n/2N2Pp1/R3B1PP/3Q1RBK b - - 5 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Nxg2  23.Nxe5  Nh4  24.Bc4  Bh3  25.hxg3  fxg3  26.Nxf7  Qd7  27.Rff2  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2q1bk1/ppp2r2/1P3n2/P2Pp2p/2N1Pp1n/2N2Ppb/R3B1PP/3Q1RBK w - - 6 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Bd3  Rg7  24.bxc7  Qc8   A.3@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/ppp2r2/1P3n2/P2Pp2p/2N1Pp1n/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 4 22@@EndFEN@@  22.bxc7  Rxc7  23.d6  Bh3   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/ppp2r2/1P3nn1/P2Pp2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK b - - 3 21@@EndFEN@@  21...cxb6!  is possibly more accurate than 21...Nh4:  22.axb6  Nh4  23.Re1  Nxg2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/pp3r2/1P3n2/3Pp2p/2N1Pp1n/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Ra2  Bh3  24.Bd3  axb6  25.Rb2  Rg7  . }
21... axb6 { Or  21...cxb6  22.axb6  a6  . } 22. Bg1
{ Or  22.axb6  Rxa1  23.Qxa1  cxd6  24.Rd1  @@StartBracket@@if @@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1p3r2/1P1p1nn1/2B1p2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/Q4R1K w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Bg1  then  24...Be6  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2bq1bk1/1p3r2/1P1p1nn1/2B1p2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/Q2R3K b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Ng4  25.fxg4  Qh4  26.Bg1  hxg4  27.Nxd6  f3  28.gxf3  Nf4  . }
22... Nh4
{ The downside of the bishop on g1 is that suddenly actual mate threats can be created on g2! }
23. Re1
{ Capturing with  23.hxg3!  , opening the king and allowing Black's pawn to stay planted is not how a human plays. In this case White is just fast enough to distract Black from landing a queen on h4, but if you're wrong in such a position it's just checkmate. The game could continue  23...fxg3  24.Be3  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1p1P1n2/P3p2p/2N1P2n/2N1BPp1/4B1P1/R2Q1R1K b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Ng6  25.dxc7  Qxc7  26.Qe1  h4  27.Nxb6  h3  28.Nxa8  Qe7  29.Qxg3  hxg2+  30.Qxg2  Rh7+  31.Kg1  Rg7  32.Kf2  Nf4  33.Qh1  Rh7  34.Nb6∞  Rxh1  35.Rxh1  Qb4   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1p1P1n2/P3p2p/2N1P2n/2N1BPp1/4B1P1/R2Q1R1K b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Bh3  25.Rg1  Be6  26.dxc7  Qxc7  27.Nb5  Qe7  28.Qd6  Ng6  29.Qxe7  Rxe7∞  .   If White instead plays  23.Nxe5  here, then Black has  23...Bh3!  . }
23... Nxg2 24. dxc7
{ 24.Kxg2  was the only move after which  24...Rg7  25.dxc7  Qe7  26.Nxe5  Qxe5  27.Bd4  gxh2+  28.Kh1  Qg5  29.Bc4+  Kh7  30.Ra2  Bh3  31.Qc2  Bc5  could follow. }
24... Nxe1
{ Gelfand missed the intermezzo. The theme of mate on g2 decides the game. }
25. Qxe1 g2+ 26. Kxg2 Rg7+ 27. Kh1 Bh3 28. Bf1 Qd3
{ The most picturesque and most accurate. The queen threatens everything and is untouchable. }
29. Nxe5
{ Of course, the queen cannot be captured due to checkmate on g2:  29.Bxd3  Bg2  . }
29... Bxf1 30. Qxf1 Qxc3 31. Rc1 Qxe5 32. c8=Q Rxc8 33. Rxc8 Qe6 *

