{ TheGelfand game is the most famous from the 9.Nd2 Ne8 line, because by this time Boris was a more famous player and the combinations are more visually striking, but it's impossible to talk about it without first mentioning this game against Alexander Beliavsky. }
1. d4
{ It occurred about six months earlier, at an otherwise completely disastrous tournament in Amsterdam where I was extremely ill. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7
9. Nd2
{ If White knows Black intends Ne8, he can reach the same starting position via the 'Bayonet' move order  9.b4  while retaining additional options:  9...Ne8  @@StartBracket@@however, if Black has other intentions, such as an early @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a5  to slow White's queenside expansion, the lines will diverge immediately, e.g.  10.bxa5  Rxa5  11.a4  @@EndBracket@@ and now:  A@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp3/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a4!?  f5  11.a5  @@StartBracket@@one of those additional options@@EndBracket@@  11...Nf6  12.Bg5  Nh5  13.Nd2  Nf4  14.c5  h6  15.Bxf4  exf4  16.Rc1  fxe4  17.Ndxe4  Nf5  18.Re1  Be5  19.Nd2  Nd4  20.Nf3  Nxf3+  21.Bxf3⩲  1/2-1/2 Kamsky,G -Nakamura,H, Saint Louis 2010.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp3/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c5  f5  11.Nd2  Nf6  transposes. }
9... Ne8
{ At the time, this was considered @@StartBracket@@maybe correctly@@EndBracket@@ dubious at best. White's queenside play was thought to be just too fast. In practice, it's far from easy over the board when you're the one getting attacked.   9...a5  @@StartBracket@@compared to Bayonet orders@@EndBracket@@  10.a3  Nd7  11.Rb1  f5  12.b4  Kh8  is probably better. }
10. b4 f5 11. c5 Nf6 12. f3
{ 12.a4!?  is Kramnik's improvement at the Olympiad. White will decide later if he needs f2-f3 or can save the tempo completely. Now Black has two main options:   A@@EndBracket@@  12...f4  13.Nc4  g5  14.Ba3  g4  15.cxd6  cxd6  16.b5  Ne8  17.Bxg4  Qc7  18.Be2  f3  19.b6  axb6  20.Nb5  fxe2  21.Qxe2  Qd8  22.Nbxd6  Nxd6  23.Bxd6  Rf7  24.Bxe5  Ng6  25.Bxg7  Nf4  26.Qe3  Qg5  27.g3  Qxg7  28.Nxb6  Bg4  29.Nxa8  Ne2+  30.Kg2  Bf3+  31.Qxf3  Rxf3  32.Kxf3  Nd4+  33.Kg2  Qf8  34.Rfe1  Qxa8  35.Red1  Nc2  36.Rac1  Qxa4  37.d6  Qxe4+  38.Kg1  Nd4  39.d7  Nf3+  40.Kf1  Nxh2+  41.Kg1  Nf3+  1/2-1/2 Kramnik,V -Nakamura,H,  Khanty-Mansiysk 2010.   B.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p1np1/2PPpp2/PP2P3/2N5/3NBPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...g5  13.Nc4  h6?!  14.f3  f4  15.Ba3  Ng6  16.b5  dxc5  17.Bxc5  Rf7  18.a5  h5  19.b6  g4  20.Nb5  cxb6  21.axb6  g3  22.Kh1  Bf8  23.d6  a6  24.Nc7  Rb8  25.Bg1  Rg7  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@1rbq1bk1/1pN2r2/pP1P1nn1/4p2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK b - - 3 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Nh7  26.Qd5  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1rbq1bk1/1pN3r1/pP1P1nn1/4p2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 4 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Re1  Nh4  27.Bf1+-   B.2@@EndBracket@@ The game 0-1 Anand, V -Nakamura, H, London 2011 varied on move 25: @@StartFEN@@1rbq1bk1/1pN2r2/pP1P1nn1/2B1p2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1R1K w - - 2 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Na5  Kh8  26.Bc4  Rg7  27.Ne6  Bxe6  28.Bxe6  gxh2  29.Nc4  Qe8  30.Bd5  h4  31.Rf2  h3  32.gxh3  Rc8  33.Ra5  Nh4  34.Kxh2  Nd7  35.Bb4  Rg3  36.Qf1  Qh5  37.Ra3  a5  38.Be1  Rxc4  39.Bxc4  Bxd6  40.Rxa5  Bc5  41.Be2  Bxb6  42.Rb5  Bd4  43.Bd1  Bxf2  44.Bxf2  Nxf3+  45.Bxf3  Qxf3  46.Rb1  Rg6  47.Rxb7  Nf6  48.Rb8+  Kh7  49.Rb7+  Kh6  . }
12... f4 13. Nc4 g5 14. a4 Ng6 15. Ba3
{ Modern correspondence may consider  15.cxd6!  a refutation of the entire line. Fortunately, chess is still played by humans, and Black's practical attacking chances are tremendous. Let's have a look:  15...cxd6  16.Nb5  Ne8  17.Kh1!?  Rf7  18.Bd2  Bf8  19.Be1  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  19...h5  20.Bf2  g4  21.fxg4  hxg4  22.Bxg4±   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqnbk1/pp3r1p/3p2n1/1N1Pp1p1/PPN1Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/R2QBR1K b - - 7 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Nf6  20.Rc1  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/pp3r1p/3p1nn1/1N1Pp1p1/PPN1Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/R2QBR1K w - - 8 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bf2  g4∞  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/pp3r1p/3p1nn1/1N1Pp1p1/PPN1Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/2RQBR1K b - - 9 20@@EndFEN@@  20...g4  21.fxg4  Nxe4  22.Bd3  Ng5  23.Nd2±   C@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqnbk1/pp3r1p/3p2n1/1N1Pp1p1/PPN1Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/R2QBR1K b - - 7 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Bd7  20.Na5  Qb8  21.Rc1  Rg7  22.Qb3  Kh8  23.Bf2  h5  24.Nxa7  Rxa7  25.Nc6  bxc6  26.Bxa7  Qxa7  27.dxc6  Bc8  28.b5  Qe7  29.b6  d5  30.Qxd5  g4  31.b7  1-0 Borstnik,A @@StartBracket@@2598@@EndBracket@@-Nefedov,S, ICCF email 2017. }
15... Rf7 16. a5 { Or  16.b5  dxc5  as in theGelfand game. } 16... h5
{ Even modern engines admit White has no advantage after  16...Bf8!  :   A.1@@EndBracket@@  17.cxd6?!  cxd6  18.Rc1  h5  19.a6  b6  20.b5  g4-+  21.Na2  Rg7  22.Nd2  Nh4  23.Qe1  g3  24.Rxc8  Rxc8  25.h3  Nh7  26.Kh1  Ng5  27.Rg1  Nxh3  28.gxh3  g2+   A.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2rq1bk1/p5r1/Pp1p4/1P1Pp1np/4Pp1n/B4PpP/N2NB1P1/4Q1RK b - - 4 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Qd7  28.Bf1  Rc2  29.Nb4  Rxd2  30.Qxd2  Nhxf3  31.gxf3  Nxf3  32.Qe2  Ng5  33.Qxh5  Nxe4  34.Kg2  Rh7  35.Qg6+  Kh8  36.Qxe4  Qxh3+  37.Kf3  Qh5+  38.Kg2  Qh2+  39.Kf3  Qh5+  40.Kg2  Qh2+  41.Kf3  Qh5+  1/2-1/2 Ramirez Alvarez,A - Delgado Ramirez,N, chess24.com INT 2019.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/ppp2r1p/3p1nn1/P1PPp1p1/1PN1Pp2/B1N2P2/4B1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.b5  dxc5  18.b6  cxb6  19.axb6  g4  20.fxg4  axb6  21.g5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/1p3r1p/1p3nn1/2pPp3/2N1PpP1/B1N5/4B1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.d6  Be6  22.Bb2  Rxa1  23.Bxa1  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/1p3r1p/1p3nn1/2pPp1P1/2N1Pp2/B1N5/4B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...b5  22.gxf6  bxc4  23.Bxc4  Kh8  . }
17. b5 dxc5 18. b6 g4
{ Technically, this is a serious mistake, as after 22.fxe4 in the game, White is probably winning.  Instead, Black could have captured once with  18...cxb6!  , then continued the attack without burning all the bridges on the queenside:  19.axb6  g4  20.Bxc5  g3  21.Kh1!  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/1p3rb1/pP3nn1/2BPp2p/2N1Ppp1/2N2P2/4B1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Rxa7  Rb8  22.Bd6?  Nh7-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/pp3rb1/1P3nn1/2BPp2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1R1K b - - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Bf8  and now:  A.1@@EndBracket@@  22.Rxa7  Rb8  23.d6  Be6  24.Nb5  Nd7!  25.Bg1  Qg5  26.Bd3?  h4  27.Ra2  h3  28.Nc7  hxg2+  29.Rxg2  Bh3  30.Rff2  Nh4  31.Bf1  Nxg2  32.Rxg2  Bxg2+  33.Bxg2  gxh2  34.Bf2  Qh5  35.Qd5  Kh8  36.Qe6  Rg7  37.Qh3  Rh7  38.Qe6  Bh6  39.Bh3  Qxf3+  0-1 Maksimenko,A -Vocaturo,D, Bastia 2016.   A.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1bk1/Rp1n1r2/1P1Pb1n1/1N2p2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/4B1PP/3Q1RBK b - - 4 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Nh4∓  26.Bd3  Nxg2  27.Kxg2  Qh4  28.Kh1  Bh3  29.Ra2  Rg7  .   A.3@@EndBracket@@ One insane computer example: @@StartFEN@@1r1q1bk1/Rp3r2/1P1Pbnn1/2B1p2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/3Q1R1K w - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Bg1  h4  25.h3  Qc8  26.Ra5!  Bxh3  27.Rxe5!  Bxg2+  28.Kxg2  h3+  29.Kh1  Nxe5  30.Nxe5  Qxc3  31.Bd4  Qb4  32.Bc4  Kh7  33.Qd3!  g2+  34.Kh2  gxf1=Q  35.Qxf1  Qd2+  36.Bf2  Nxe4  37.fxe4  Rf6  38.Nf3  Qc3  39.Bd3  Rxd6  40.Bd4  Rxd4  41.Qxh3+  Bh6  42.Qf5+  Kh8  43.Qe5+  Kh7  44.Qf5+   B.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/pp3r2/1P3nn1/2BPp2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1PP/R2Q1R1K w - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22.d6  a6  23.Bg1  Be6  24.Ra5  Nd7  25.Qd2  Rc8  26.Nd5  Nh4  27.Rc1!  Nxg2  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@2rq1bk1/1p1n1r2/pP1Pb3/R2Np2p/2N1Pp1n/5Pp1/3QB1PP/2R3BK b - - 9 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Bh3  28.Bf1  Nxf3  29.Qa2!  Bg4  30.gxf3  Bxf3+  31.Bg2  Bxg2+  32.Qxg2  Qg5  33.Nc7  f3  34.Qxg3  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2rq1bk1/1p1n1r2/pP1Pb3/R2Np2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/3QB1nP/2R3BK w - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Nc7!  Ne3  29.Nxe3  fxe3  30.Qxe3  Rg7  31.hxg3  Bf7  32.Rd1  Rxg3  33.Bh2±   B.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2rq1bk1/1p1n1r2/pP1Pb1n1/R2Np2p/2N1Pp2/5Pp1/3QB1PP/5RBK b - - 7 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Rc6!?  @@StartBracket@@  keeping tabs on both white pawns, and getting out in front of possible Nc7 ideas  @@EndBracket@@  27.Rd1  Qg5∞  . }
19. bxc7 Rxc7 20. Nb5 g3 21. Nxc7 Nxe4
{ The point. Extremely thematic, clearing the way for Qh4 with a classic KID attack. }
22. Ne6
{ Typically, computers spoil the brilliancy. The machine is cold blooded, and says it has collected plenty of material that it will happily give back to avoid mate and go on to win:  22.fxe4!  22...Qh4  23.h3  Bxh3  24.gxh3  Qxh3  25.Rf2!  gxf2+  26.Kxf2  Qg3+  27.Kf1  f3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r5k1/ppN3b1/6n1/P1pPp2p/2N1Pp2/B5q1/4B3/R2Q1K2 b - - 2 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Qh3+  28.Ke1  Qc3+  29.Qd2  Qxa1+  30.Bd1  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r5k1/ppN3b1/6n1/P1pPp2p/2N1P3/B4pq1/4B3/R2Q1K2 w - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Nxa8  fxe2+  29.Kxe2!  Nf4+  30.Kd2  Qd3+  31.Kc1  Qxc4+  32.Qc2±  . }
22... Bxe6 23. dxe6 gxh2+ 24. Kxh2 Qh4+ 25. Kg1 Ng3 26. Bxc5 e4 27. Ra4 Rc8
{ Or  27...Qg5!?  28.Bxa7  b5  29.Ra2  bxc4  30.e7  Qh4  31.Qd7  Qh1+  32.Kf2  e3+  33.Ke1  Nxf1  34.Bxc4+  Kh7  35.Bxf1  Qh4+  36.Kd1  Nxe7=  . }
28. Bxa7
{ The last chance for White to hold the game was  28.e7  Nxe7  29.Nd6  exf3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@2r3k1/pp2n1b1/3N4/P1B4p/R3pp1q/5Pn1/4B1P1/3Q1RK1 b - - 1 29@@EndFEN@@  29...Rxc5  30.Nxe4+-  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2r3k1/pp2n1b1/3N4/P1B4p/R4p1q/5pn1/4B1P1/3Q1RK1 w - - 0 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Bc4+  Kh8  31.Nf7+  Kg8  32.Ng5+  Kh8  33.Nxf3  Qh1+  34.Kf2  Ne4+  35.Ke1  Qxg2  36.Bd4  Qg3+  37.Bf2  Bc3+  38.Ke2  Qg2  39.Be6  Ng3+  40.Kd3  Rc6  41.Bxg3  Qxg3  42.Qe2  Qg6+  43.Qe4  Rxe6  44.Qxg6  Re3+  45.Kc4  Nxg6  46.Ra3  Ne5+  47.Nxe5  Bxe5  48.Rxe3  fxe3=  . }
28... b5 29. Rb4 { If  29.axb6  then  29...Bd4+  . } 29... bxc4 30. Bxc4 Qh1+
31. Kf2 e3+ 32. Bxe3 fxe3+ 33. Kxe3 Nxf1+ 34. Bxf1 Qg1+ *

