[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.  Positional Battles and Complex Struggles"]
[Black "Game 6: Levon Aronian vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Moscow 2010"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Tal Memorial in 2010 was the strongest tournament I'd played up to that point in my career. In round 7  (of 9)  the field was pretty tight, with Aronian and Mamedyarov leading on +2. I was half a point back at +1. }
1. d4
{ I had already entered the live top 10 for the first time after beating Eljanov earlier in the tournament, but I had a chance now to fight for first in the third strongest tournament @@StartBracket@@by avg. rating at the time@@EndBracket@@ in history. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 { What better way to fight than the KID! } 4. g3
{ Levon opts for a sane, flexible approach. In the Fianchetto, White won't have to face the kingside attacks we usually associate with the KID. On the other hand, he won't be smashing through on the queenside either. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O a6
{ The Panno system. Black intends Rb8 and b5 in most cases, but is still flexible enough to switch to dark-squared play in the center with e5, depending on how white continues. }
8. d5
{ The most classical approach. White has many alternative tries:   8.h3   8.Qd3   8.b3  Rb8   8.Bf4   8.e4  Bg4  9.Be3  Nd7  10.Qd2  Bxf3  11.Bxf3  e5  . }
8... Na5 9. Nd2
{ 9.b3  is the other way for White to continue and usually signals that White intends to meet c5 with dxc6:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/n2P4/2P5/1PN2NP1/P3PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5  10.dxc6  Nxc6  11.Bb2   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/n2P4/2P5/1PN2NP1/P3PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rb8  10.Bg5  c5  11.dxc6 }
9... c5 10. Rb1 Rb8 11. b3 b5 12. Bb2 Bh6
{ Black makes a concrete threat to win the pawn on c4 by capturing the knight first. }
13. Ba1
{ Still theory, and the best way of meeting Bh6.   After  13.e3?!  bxc4  14.Nxc4  Nxc4  15.bxc4  Qa5  16.Ba1  Bd7  Black is very comfortable.  17.Rb3  Bg7  18.a3  Ng4∓  19.Bf3  Ne5  20.Be2  Bh3  21.Re1  Nd7  22.Rxb8  Rxb8  23.Ne4  Bf5  24.Bxg7  Bxe4  25.Bh6  Ne5  26.Rf1  Qxa3  27.f3  Bd3  28.Bxd3  Qxd3  29.Qxd3  Nxd3  30.Ra1  Rb6  31.e4  Ne5  32.Kf2  Rb2+  0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ -Kasimdzhanov,R @@StartBracket@@2690@@EndBracket@@ Vitoria Gasteiz 2007. }
13... Bf5
{ Taking the pawn straight off is possible, but very risky:  13...Bxd2  14.Qxd2  bxc4  15.bxc4  With the bishop tucked away safely on a1, the situation on the b-file has to be addressed, and White will have a strong initiative in the center for his sacrificed pawn, in addition to Black's dark-squared weakness around his king:  15...Nxc4  16.Qf4  Rxb1  17.Nxb1  Nb6  18.e4  and @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/4pp1p/p2p1np1/n1pP4/2P5/2N3P1/P2QPPBP/BR3RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Rxb1  16.Nxb1!  Nxc4  17.Qd3  Nb6  18.e4=∞  . }
14. e4 Bg4 15. f3
{ Or  15.Qc2!?  Bxd2  16.Qxd2  bxc4  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  17.bxc4  Nxc4  18.Qd3  Ne5!  19.Qxa6?  @@StartBracket@@if @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/p2p1np1/2pPn3/4P1b1/2NQ2P1/P4PBP/BR3RK1 w - - 2 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Qe3  then  19...Nc4=  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/Q2p1np1/2pPn3/4P1b1/2N3P1/P4PBP/BR3RK1 b - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Ra8  20.Qb5  Bf3∓   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/p2p1np1/n1pP4/2p1P1b1/1PN3P1/P2Q1PBP/BR3RK1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.h3!  Bd7  18.bxc4  Nxc4  19.Qe2  Na3  20.Rxb8  Qxb8  21.Rc1  Nb5∞  . }
15... Be3+ 16. Kh1 Bd7 17. cxb5
{ 17.f4!  was the only way for White to seek an advantage:   A@@EndBracket@@  17...bxc4  18.e5!  Ne8  19.bxc4  Bxd2  20.Qxd2  Nxc4  21.Rxb8  Qxb8  22.Qe2  Na3  23.e6  Bb5  24.Qb2⩲   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3bpp1p/p2p1np1/nppP4/2P1PP2/1PN1b1P1/P2N2BP/BR1Q1R1K b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bd4  18.Ne2  Bxa1  19.Rxa1  e6  20.h3  bxc4  21.bxc4  exd5  22.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3b1p1p/p2p1np1/n1pp4/2P1PP2/6PP/P2NN1B1/R2Q1R1K w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.e5!?  dxe5  23.fxe5  Nh5  24.g4  Qh4  25.gxh5  Bxh3  26.Qe1  Qxh5  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3b1p1p/p2p1np1/n1pP4/4PP2/6PP/P2NN1B1/R2Q1R1K b - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Rb4!  @@StartBracket@@Black is just fast enough with his pieces on the queenside to avoid getting steamrolled@@EndBracket@@  23.Nc3  Rd4  24.Qc2  Nc4  25.Nxc4  Rxc4  .   17.Ne2  bxc4  18.bxc4  Rb4  19.Rxb4  cxb4  20.Qc2  Qc7  is not as good. }
17... axb5 18. Ne2 e5
{ A missed opportunity. With  18...b4!  White would be the one hoping for equality:   A@@EndBracket@@  19.f4  Bb5  20.h3  c4⩱  or @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/3p1np1/nbpP4/1p2PP2/1P2b1P1/P2NN1BP/BR1Q1R1K w - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Rf3  Ng4  21.Qe1  Bd3   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3bpp1p/3p1np1/n1pP4/1p2P3/1P2bPP1/P2NN1BP/BR1Q1R1K w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Qc2  Bb5  20.Rfe1  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/3p1np1/nbpP4/1p2P3/1P2bPP1/P1QNN1BP/BR3R1K w - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Nc4  Bxc4  21.bxc4  Nd7  22.a3  Qb6  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/4pp1p/3p1np1/nbpP4/1p2P3/1P2bPP1/P1QNN1BP/BR2R2K b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Bf2  21.Rf1  Be3  . }
19. dxe6
{ Or  19.f4!?  Bd4  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3b1p1p/3p1np1/nppPp3/4PP2/1P2b1P1/P2NN1BP/BR1Q1R1K b - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Ng4  20.h3  Nf2+  21.Rxf2  Bxf2  22.fxe5  dxe5  23.Bxe5=∞  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/3b1p1p/3p1np1/nppPp3/3bPP2/1P4P1/P2NN1BP/BR1Q1R1K w - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Nxd4  cxd4  21.Nf3  Bg4  22.Qd3  Bxf3  23.Qxf3  Nd7  24.fxe5  dxe5  25.Bb2  . }
19... fxe6 20. e5 { Levon breaks before I have a chance to play e6-e5 myself. }
20... dxe5 21. Bxe5 Rc8 22. Bxf6
{ White needed to eliminate the Nf6 to secure e4 for his own, and to prevent it from landing on d5.   Another option was  22.Nc3  Bd4  23.f4  b4  24.Bxf6  Qxf6  25.Nce4  Qe7  . }
22... Qxf6 23. Ne4
{ Black has two bishops in a now open position, White has a better structure, a great knight on e4 and no real weaknesses. It should be about equal. }
23... Qe7 24. Qd3 Bh6 25. f4 Bc6 26. Rbd1 Nb7
{ 26...Bg7  27.Qe3  c4  was a more straightforward way of dealing with the queenside. }
27. Qe3 b4 28. Nc1 Bd5 29. Nd3 c4 30. bxc4 Bxc4 31. Qb6 Rfd8 32. Nxb4 Bxf1 33.
Rxf1 Rf8 34. a4 Kh8
{ Stepping out of any checks, to be able to meet a5 with Qc7, should now be holding straightforwardly.   If  34...Bg7  then  35.a5  and it's getting uncomfortable }
35. h4 { Or  35.a5  Qc7  . } 35... Bg7 36. a5 Qc7 37. Ng5 Nxa5 38. Qxc7 Rxc7
39. Nxe6 Rc3 40. Nd5 Rxg3 41. Nxf8 Bxf8 42. Rc1 Rg4 43. Kh2 Rxh4+ 44. Kg3 g5
45. Rc8 Kg7 46. Ra8 Nc6 47. fxg5 Rd4 48. Nf6 Ne7 49. Be4 h6 50. Nh5+ Kf7 51.
Bb1 hxg5 52. Ba2+ Kg6 53. Ra6+ Kxh5 54. Bf7+ Ng6 55. Rxg6 Rd3+ 56. Kg2 Kh4 57.
Be6 Rg3+ 58. Kh2 Rc3 59. Kg2 Rc6 60. Bf5 Rxg6 *

