1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Nd2 a5
{ This was considered the main line until  9...Ne8  was resurrected from the dead a few years later. }
10. a3
{ 10.Rb1  c5  doesn't change much, and is likely to transpose back to the game:  11.dxc6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2npbp/3p1np1/p1pPp3/2P1P3/2N5/PP1NBPPP/1RBQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.a3  Ne8  transposes  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2npbp/2Pp1np1/p3p3/2P1P3/2N5/PP1NBPPP/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...bxc6  12.Nf3  c5=  and Black enjoys a nice outpost on d4.   After 10.Rb1 the main line is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1npbp/3p1np1/p2Pp3/2P1P3/2N5/PP1NBPPP/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nd7  11.a3  f5  12.b4  with over 1000 games featuring prominent players like Kramnik and Kasparov. }
10... c5
{ Trying to lock up the center of the board, with a very simple plan of attacking on the kingside. }
11. Rb1 Ne8 { Planning ...f5 next. } 12. b4
{ White tries to get in on the action faster on the queenside. } 12... axb4 13.
axb4 b6 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Nb3 f5 16. f3 f4
{ All-in! Will Black's attack break through before White crashes in on the queenside? }
17. Bd2 Bd7 18. Ra1 g5 19. Nb5
{ Or  19.Rxa8  Qxa8  20.Qc2  Qd8  21.Ra1  h5⇆  with the idea of blowing up the kingside with ...Ng6, ...g4 and ...Nh4. }
19... Rxa1 20. Qxa1 Nc8 21. g4
{ My opponent was clearly very unsettled with the prospect of having to defend against an attack.   21.Na5  was much better. No fear!  21...g4  22.Nc6  Qg5  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@2nqnrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp3/2P1Ppp1/5P2/3BB1PP/Q4RK1 b - - 1 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Qh4  23.fxg4  Bxg4  24.Qd1  White should be better due to the placement of the knights  @@EndBracket@@. And now:  A@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n1nrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp1q1/2P1Ppp1/5P2/3BB1PP/Q4RK1 w - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Qd1  g3!   A.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n1nrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp1q1/2P1Pp2/5Pp1/3BB1PP/3Q1RK1 w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.h3?  will get White into trouble very quickly:  24...Rf6  25.Nb8  Bxh3!  26.gxh3  g2  @@StartBracket@@an important move, as otherwise White may block the kingside with Kg2@@EndBracket@@  27.Rf2  Rg6  @@StartBracket@@  threatening ...Qg3-Qxh3-Qh1#  @@EndBracket@@  28.Bf1  gxf1=Q+  29.Kxf1  Nb6-+  with the threat of ...Nxc4 and Black is completely winning.   A.2@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n1nrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp1q1/2P1Pp2/5Pp1/3BB1PP/3Q1RK1 w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.hxg3  Qxg3→  The computer shows 0.00 in this case, but White has to be very careful as Black has tremendous attacking potential.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n1nrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp1q1/2P1Ppp1/5P2/3BB1PP/Q4RK1 w - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23.fxg4  Nf6  24.Bf3  Bxg4  25.Qd1  h5  White is better, but Black definitely has play.   C@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n1nrk1/3b2bp/2Np4/1NpPp1q1/2P1Ppp1/5P2/3BB1PP/Q4RK1 w - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Nb8!  @@StartBracket@@a computer move if I've ever seen one@@EndBracket@@  23...gxf3  24.Bxf3  Bg4  25.Qd1  h5  and once again, White remains slightly better, but Black has play. }
21... fxg3 22. hxg3 Qf6 23. Qc1 Qg6 24. Nc3
{ A prophylactic move. White prepares for the ...g4 push in advance by protecting the e4-pawn.   24.g4  Nf6  25.Rf2  h5  The computer once again says that White is fine, but for a human this feels very dangerous. }
24... h6 25. Na1
{ Too slow of a plan.  25.g4=  should be enough for equality. White's idea should be to bring the rook over to the h-file in order to defend against ...h5 ideas. }
25... Nf6 26. Nc2 g4 { Finally. } 27. Qe1
{ 27.Ne3  was the best move. The game could continue  27...gxf3  28.Rxf3  Nxe4  29.Rxf8+  Bxf8  30.Nxe4  Qxe4  31.Bh5  Another absurd computer move @@StartBracket@@and the only move!@@EndBracket@@ with the threat of bringing the queen to f7 via f1, after which White is completely fine.  31...Be7  32.Qf1  Kh8!  @@StartBracket@@Black should avoid @@StartFEN@@2n3k1/3bb3/3p3p/2pPp2B/2P1q3/4N1P1/3B4/5QK1 b - - 3 32@@EndFEN@@  32...Qh7?  because of  33.Ng4±  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2n4k/3bb3/3p3p/2pPp2B/2P1q3/4N1P1/3B4/5QK1 w - - 4 33@@EndFEN@@  33.Qf7  Qh7  34.Qf3  Qd3=  with a repetition to follow. }
27... gxf3 28. Bxf3 Nb6
{ Too slow of a move which can only help White.  28...h5!  was definitely better:  29.Ne3  Bh6  @@StartBracket@@a move with many purposes: Black frees up the g7-square for the rook, and has ...Bf4 ideas to put further pressure on the g3-pawn@@EndBracket@@  30.Kh2  Rf7  when White is under pressure. }
29. Ne3 { Now the White knight is perfectly placed. } 29... Bh3 30. Bg2 Bxg2
31. Nf5
{ Even though White will be down a pawn in the resulting position, the outposted knight on f5 more than makes up for it. }
31... Rf7 32. Kxg2 Nxc4 33. Qe2
{ 33.Bc1  Considering the narrow path White has to walk in the game after 33.Qe2 this would have been preferable.  After  33...Nh5  34.Rf3  the game is equal. }
33... Nxd2 34. Qxd2 Nxe4
{ Trading White's strong knight on f5 and going into an endgame in which White has to be careful. }
35. Nxe4 Rxf5 36. Rxf5 Qxf5 37. Nxd6 Qg6 { The moment of truth. } 38. Nb5
{ Huge mistake. The only way to hold the draw was  38.Nc8  Qe4+  39.Kh2  Qd4  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@2N3k1/6b1/7p/2pPp3/4q3/6P1/3Q3K/8 b - - 4 39@@EndFEN@@  39...c4  40.d6  Bf6  41.d7  Qd4  42.Qxh6  Qf2+  followed by a perpetual  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2N3k1/6b1/7p/2pPp3/3q4/6P1/3Q3K/8 w - - 5 40@@EndFEN@@  40.Qa2  e4  41.d6+  c4  42.Ne7+  Kf7  43.Nc6  Qc5  @@StartBracket@@if @@StartFEN@@8/5kb1/2NP3p/8/2pqp3/6P1/Q6K/8 b - - 3 43@@EndFEN@@  43...Qxd6  then  44.Qxc4+=  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/5kb1/2NP3p/2q5/2p1p3/6P1/Q6K/8 w - - 4 44@@EndFEN@@  44.d7  Qh5+  45.Kg2  Qf3+  Once again, we reach a draw by perpetual check.   38.Nb7??  is an even bigger mistake as it forces the trade of queens via  38...Qe4+  39.Kf2  Qb4-+  . }
38... Qe4+ 39. Kh2 Qb4 40. Qe2
{ This does not help much either. Of course White cannot play  40.Qxb4  cxb4  41.d6  Kf7  42.Kg2  b3  43.Kf3  b2  44.Na3  Ke6  45.Ke3  Bf8-+  . }
40... c4 41. Nc7 c3 42. Qa6 c2
{ There is no miracle repetition that will save White. } 43. Qc8+
{ Or  43.Qe6+  Kh8  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  44.Qc8+  Qf8   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@7k/2N3b1/4Q2p/3Pp3/1q6/6P1/2p4K/8 w - - 2 44@@EndFEN@@  44.Qc6  Qd2+-+   C@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@7k/2N3b1/4Q2p/3Pp3/1q6/6P1/2p4K/8 w - - 2 44@@EndFEN@@  44.Qe8+  Qf8  45.Qc6  Qf2+  46.Kh3  Qf1+-+  . }
43... Qf8 44. Ne8 c1=Q
{ 44...Qf2+  is objectively better, but it is possible to see ghosts. After  45.Kh3  Qf1+  46.Kh2  c1=Q  47.Nf6+  Kf7  48.Qe6+  Kg6  49.Ne8+  Kh7  Black is clearly winning. }
