1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 g5 13. Rc1 Ng6 14. Nb5
{ The main line these days is  14.c5  Nxc5  15.b4  Na6  16.Nb5  Bd7  . } 14...
b6 15. b4 a6 16. Nc3 Rf7 17. Nd3 h5 18. c5 bxc5
{ 'Improving' @@StartBracket@@if you can call it that@@EndBracket@@ on my previous game against Anish Giri from 2011:  18...Bf8  19.cxb6  cxb6  20.b5  .   Let's see what could have happened after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/3n1r2/pp1p2n1/3Pp1pp/1P2Pp2/2NN1P2/P3BBPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Nb2!?  :   A@@EndBracket@@  20...Nf6  21.Nca4!  b5  22.Nb6  Rb8  23.Nxc8  Rxc8  24.Nd3  and it is very hard to believe in any King's Indian attack without a light-squared bishop.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/3n1r2/pp1p2n1/3Pp1pp/1P2Pp2/2N2P2/PN2BBPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Rb8  21.Nc4  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@1rbq1bk1/3n1r2/pp1p2n1/3Pp1pp/1P2Pp2/2N2P2/PN2BBPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Nca4  b5  22.Nc3  Nf6→  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1rbq1bk1/3n1r2/pp1p2n1/3Pp1pp/1PN1Pp2/2N2P2/P3BBPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 3 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Nf6⇆  A very complicated position, but without a clear breakthrough on the queenside, it should always be easier to play for Black.   Now back to the Anish Giri game. After 20.b5 it continued @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/3n1r2/pp1p2n1/1P1Pp1pp/4Pp2/2NN1P2/P3BBPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20...a5  21.Na4  Nc5  22.Ndxc5  dxc5  23.d6?  @@StartBracket@@ I remember analyzing the position after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/5r2/1p4n1/pPpPp1pp/N3Pp2/5P2/P3BBPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Nb2  Bd6  24.Nc4  Rg7  25.Kh1  in depth with Anish after our game in Reggio Emilia, and we both concluded that White should be better due to long term ideas involving Rg1 and g3@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1bk1/5r2/1p1P2n1/pPp1p1pp/N3Pp2/5P2/P3BBPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Be6  24.Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@a complete miscalculation by Anish@@EndBracket@@  24...bxc5  25.Nxc5  Bxa2  26.Qa4  Bxd6  27.Qxa2  Bxc5+  28.Kh1  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r2q2k1/5r2/6n1/pPb1p1pp/4Pp2/5P2/Q3B1PP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Rxc5  Qd4+  29.Kh1  Qxc5-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2q2k1/5r2/6n1/pPb1p1pp/4Pp2/5P2/Q3B1PP/2R2R1K b - - 1 28@@EndFEN@@  28...Bd4  29.Bc4  Raa7  30.Bxf7+  Rxf7∓  @@StartBracket@@Giri-Nakamura, Reggio Emilia 2011@@EndBracket@@. }
19. bxc5 Bf8 20. cxd6 Bxd6 21. Na4 Nf6 22. Ndc5
{ 22.Nac5  was preferable as the knight on d3 targets e5/f4 and you don't have a knight on the rim. After  22...Rg7  23.Qa4!  g4  24.Qc6  the computer claims White is winning, but it is very, very hard for a human to play this line without knowing the evaluation and facing a very dangerous kingside attack. }
22... Rg7 23. Ne6 Bxe6 24. dxe6 Qe7 25. Nc5 Kh8
{ Apparently Black is fine after  25...g4  26.fxg4  hxg4  27.Bxg4  Nxg4  28.Qxg4  Nf8  but this isn't in the spirit of the King's Indian at all. }
26. Nb7 Ba3 27. Rc3 Bb4 28. Rd3 Qxe6
{ If  28...Rag8?  29.Nd8!  the white knight gets into the game in a major way. And now:   A@@EndBracket@@  29...Kh7  30.Nc6  Qf8  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@6r1/2p1q1rk/p1N1Pnn1/4p1pp/1b2Pp2/3R1P2/P3BBPP/3Q1RK1 b - - 12 30@@EndFEN@@  30...Qxe6  31.Nxb4+-  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@5qr1/2p3rk/p1N1Pnn1/4p1pp/1b2Pp2/3R1P2/P3BBPP/3Q1RK1 w - - 13 31@@EndFEN@@  31.Rd8  Ne8  32.Rxe8  Qxe8  33.Nxb4  and White should win the game now.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@3N2rk/2p1q1r1/p3Pnn1/2b1p1pp/4Pp2/3R1P2/P3BBPP/3Q1RK1 w - - 11 30@@EndFEN@@  29...Bc5  30.Nf7+  Kh7  31.Nxg5+  Kh8  32.Nf7+  Kh7  . }
29. Qb3
{ A very logical move as Black will have no attack with queens off the board, and the extra pawn isn't worth very much. }
29... Qxb3 30. Rxb3 a5 31. Rc1 g4 32. Kf1
{ It was important to bring the knight back into the game with  32.Nc5  g3  @@StartBracket@@no doubt what Rustam was worried about; if instead @@StartFEN@@r6k/2p3r1/5nn1/p1N1p2p/1b2Ppp1/1R3P2/P3BBPP/2R3K1 b - - 1 32@@EndFEN@@  32...gxf3  33.gxf3  Black has no good discoveries  33...Nh4+  34.Kh1  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r6k/2p3r1/5nn1/p1N1p2p/1b2Pp2/1R3Pp1/P3BBPP/2R3K1 w - - 0 33@@EndFEN@@  33.hxg3  fxg3  34.Bxg3  h4  35.Bh2  Nh5  36.Ne6!  Re7  37.Rc6  Ngf4  and the position is equal, but unlike the game, the re-routing of the knight makes a huge difference. }
32... g3
{ Thematic, but  32...h4  was probably better:  33.Rc6  g3  34.h3  @@StartBracket@@a ridiculous computer idea@@EndBracket@@  34...Nxe4  35.fxe4  gxf2  36.Nc5  and the position is balanced. }
33. hxg3 fxg3 34. Bxg3 h4 35. Bf2
{ Or  35.Bh2  Nh5  36.Nc5  Ngf4  and Black is completely winning. } 35... Nh5
36. f4 Nhxf4 37. Bg4 Rf8 38. a3 Bd6 39. Nxa5 Ne7
{ Better was  39...Nxg2  40.Kxg2  Nf4+  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@5r1k/2p3r1/3b2n1/N3p3/4P1Bp/PR6/5BK1/2R5 b - - 0 40@@EndFEN@@  40...Ne7  41.Bxh4  Rxg4+  42.Kh3  Rxe4  43.Bxe7  Bxe7  44.Rxc7=  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@5r1k/2p3r1/3b4/N3p3/4PnBp/PR6/5BK1/2R5 w - - 1 41@@EndFEN@@  41.Kf3  Nd3+  42.Bf5  Nxc1  43.Rc3  Rxf5+  @@StartBracket@@not @@StartFEN@@5r1k/2p3r1/3b4/N3pB2/4P2p/P1R2K2/5B2/2n5 b - - 1 43@@EndFEN@@  43...Na2  44.Rc2  and the knight is trapped on the edge@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@7k/2p3r1/3b4/N3pr2/4P2p/P1R2K2/5B2/2n5 w - - 0 44@@EndFEN@@  44.exf5  e4+  45.Kxe4  Ne2  46.Rh3  Ng3+=  . }
40. Bf3 h3 41. gxh3 Nxh3 42. Ke2
{ The endgame is balanced, although it is always easier for Black to play with the knights and White's king being more open. }
42... Ng5 43. Nc4 Ng6 44. Rh1+ Kg8 45. Nd2 Nf4+ 46. Kd1 Ra8
{ Trying to go after the weak pawns on a3 and e4. } 47. Nc4 Ra4 48. Nxd6 cxd6
49. Rh6 Rf7 50. Rxd6 Nfh3 51. Ke2 Rc4 52. Bb6 Rc2+ 53. Kd1 Rh2 54. Be2 Nxe4 55.
Rd8+ Kg7 56. Re3 Nhg5 57. a4 Rf6 58. Rd7+ Kg6 59. a5
{ After defending very well for many moves, Rustam makes a fatal blunder.   59.Ba5  Rc6  60.Be1=  would still hold. }
59... Rc6 60. Bd3
{ Some other lines:  A@@EndBracket@@  60.Bf3  Rc4  61.Bxe4+  Nxe4  62.Rc7  Ra4  and White is completely lost due to the placement of the king.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/1Br3k1/P3p1n1/4n3/4R3/4B2r/3K4 w - - 1 60@@EndFEN@@  60.Ba6  Nf2+  61.Kd2  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/BBr3k1/P3p1n1/8/4R3/5n1r/3K4 w - - 3 61@@EndFEN@@  61.Ke1  Rc1+  62.Kd2  Rd1+  63.Kc3  Rxd7  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/BBr3k1/P3p1n1/8/4R3/3K1n1r/8 b - - 4 61@@EndFEN@@  61...Nge4+  62.Ke2  Rc2+  63.Kf3  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/BB4k1/P3p3/4n3/4R3/2r1Kn1r/8 w - - 7 63@@EndFEN@@  63.Kf1  Nd3!  64.Rd6+  Kh5  65.Rdxd3  Rh1  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/BB4k1/P3p3/4n3/4RK2/2r2n1r/8 b - - 8 63@@EndFEN@@  63...Ng5+  64.Kg3  Nh1+  65.Kg4  Rcg2+  66.Rg3  Rxg3   C@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/3R4/1Br3k1/P3p1n1/4n3/4R3/4B2r/3K4 w - - 1 60@@EndFEN@@  60.Bg4  Nf2+  61.Ke1  Nxg4  . }
60... Rd2+ { White resigned in view of  61.Ke1  Rc1  . } *

