[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Game 9: Magnus Carlsen vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Online Rapid 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ To set the stage this was the final game of the 5th match between Magnus and me in the Magnus Carlsen Chess Tour Finals in 2020. The matches had been very back and forth and we were tied 2-2 but in this final game of the 5th match I was trailing 2-1 and in a must-win situation, so I decided to play the King's Indian! }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
{ 6...e5  is the regular move, but in a must-win situation you cannot play it as White can force an endgame with very drawish outcomes by playing the exchange variation of the King's Indian:  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Bg5  . }
7. O-O e5 8. Be3 Ng4 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bh4 h5 11. h3 Nh6 12. Bg3 Kh7 13. Qc2
{ After  13.Qd2  Nf7  14.Rad1  c6  15.b4  Qe7  16.Rfe1  Rd8  17.a3  White has much more space and is better as in most King's Indian lines. However, if Black can get in ...g5, ...Nf8 and ...Ng6 there are always chances as seen in Roiz-Radjabov, Bursa 2010. }
13... c6 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. c5
{ Not a horrible move, but one after which the game becomes extremely complicated which is exactly what I wanted considering the match situation.  The computer evaluates  15.b4  as simply winning for White due to the unstoppable ideas of b5 and c5:  15...Re8  16.b5  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b1r3/pp1nq1bk/2pp1ppn/4p2p/1PPPP3/2N2NBP/P1Q1BPP1/3R1RK1 w - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16.c5  dxc5  17.bxc5  Nf8  18.Rfe1  Nf7  19.Na4  is positionally lost for Black  @@EndBracket@@ and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1r3/pp1nq1bk/2pp1ppn/1P2p2p/2PPP3/2N2NBP/P1Q1BPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...g5  17.c5  dxc5  18.dxe5  fxe5  19.bxc6  bxc6  20.h4  g4  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1b1r3/p2nq1bk/2p4n/2p1p1pp/4P2P/2N2NB1/P1Q1BPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20...gxh4  21.Nxh4+-  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b1r3/p2nq1bk/2p4n/2p1p2p/4P1pP/2N2NB1/P1Q1BPP1/3R1RK1 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Ng5+  Kh8  22.Qa4  Bb7  23.Qa5+-   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1r3/pp1nq1bk/2pp1ppn/1P2p2p/2PPP3/2N2NBP/P1Q1BPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nf8  17.c5  dxc5  18.dxe5  fxe5  19.bxc6  bxc6  20.Bh4  Bf6  21.Bxf6  Qxf6  22.Na4  @@StartBracket@@White is completely winning, as Black doesn't really have an attack on the kingside  @@EndBracket@@  22...g5  23.Nxc5  g4  24.hxg4  hxg4  25.Nh2  Ng6  26.Nd7+-  . }
15... dxc5 16. d5 Nb6 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Na4 Nxa4 19. Qxa4 Rb8 20. b3 Rb4 21.
Qxc6 Bb7 22. Qd7
{ 22.Rd7  Bxc6  23.Rxe7  Rf7  24.Rxf7  Nxf7  25.Rc1!  Bf8  26.Ne1  Bxe4  27.f3  Bf5  28.Bf2  Despite being down a pawn White will pick up the pawn on c5 in a couple of moves and equalize easily. }
22... Rf7 23. Qxe7 Rxe7 24. Nd2 Bxe4
{ Black is up a pawn and has a superior pawn structure in the middle of the board. }
25. Nxe4 Rxe4 26. Bc4 Rd4
{ An important move as it shuts down any White counterplay on the file. } 27.
f3 { Not  27.Rxd4  cxd4-+  . } 27... Red7 28. Ra1 Nf5 29. Bf2 Bh6
{ In a must-win game, this move is not hard to spot. } 30. Rfe1
{ Or  30.Bxd4  cxd4  31.Rfd1  Be3+  32.Kf1  Ng3+  33.Ke1  f5  and Black is easily winning. }
30... Bd2 31. Bxd4 cxd4 32. Red1 Be3+ 33. Kh2 h4 34. b4 Bf4+ 35. Kg1 Ne3 36.
Rdc1 d3 37. Bb5 Rd4 38. Rc7+ Kh6 39. Rd7 Rxb4
{ 39...Nd5  is a difficult move to play under time pressure, but it is a lot more clean than the game:  40.Ba4  Nc3  41.Rxd4  exd4  42.Bb3  d2  43.a4  Be3+  44.Kf1  d3  45.b5  Ne2-+  and @@StartFEN@@8/p7/5ppk/8/PP5p/1BnpbP1P/3p2P1/R4K2 w - - 0 45@@EndFEN@@  45.Bd1  Kg5  46.b5  Bd4  when White cannot push the pawns further up the board. }
40. Bxd3 Rb2 41. Bf1
{ Black is still winning technically, but there is no clear path to victory. }
41... Nf5 { Or  41...Nc2  42.Rad1  Rxa2-+  . } 42. a4 Be3+ 43. Kh2 Bd4 44. Rc1
Ne3 45. a5 Rf2 46. Kg1 Ra2 47. a6 Nxf1+
{ Better was  47...Bb6!  48.Kh1  Kg5  49.Bd3  f5∓  .  There is still no easy to victory, but Black can keep advancing and improving the piece placement on the kingside. }
48. Kxf1 Rf2+ 49. Ke1 Rxg2 50. f4
{ White should have played  50.Rc6!  Rg1+  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/p2R4/P1R2ppk/4p3/3b3p/5P1P/6r1/4K3 b - - 1 50@@EndFEN@@  50...f5  51.f4=  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@8/p2R4/P1R2ppk/4p3/3b3p/5P1P/8/4K1r1 w - - 2 51@@EndFEN@@  51.Kd2  f5  52.f4  @@StartBracket@@White is holding comfortably as the bishop on d4 is overloaded@@EndBracket@@  52...Rg2+  53.Kd1  Rg1+=  . }
50... Rg1+ 51. Kd2 Be3+ 52. Kxe3 Rxc1 53. fxe5 Re1+
{ A serious error.  53...fxe5  54.Rxa7  Rc3+  55.Ke4  Rxh3  56.Kxe5  Ra3  57.Ra8  Kg5-+  was the way to go. }
54. Kf3 { Amazingly  54.Kf2!  Rxe5  55.Rxa7  draw. } 54... Rxe5 55. Rxa7 Ra5
56. Ra8 Ra3+
{ Better was  56...Kg5  57.a7  Ra2  58.Ke4  Ra3  59.Kd5  f5  60.Kc6  Kf4  61.Kb6  Rb3+  62.Kc5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@R7/P7/1K4p1/5p2/5k1p/1r5P/8/8 w - - 4 62@@EndFEN@@  62.Kc6  Rxh3  63.Rb8  Ra3  64.a8=Q  Rxa8  65.Rxa8  h3-+  @@EndBracket@@ and now:  A.1@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@R7/P7/6p1/2K2p2/5k1p/1r5P/8/8 b - - 5 62@@EndFEN@@  62...Rxh3??  63.Rb8  Ra3  64.a8=Q  Rxa8  65.Rxa8  h3  66.Rh8  Kg3  67.Rg8=  .   A.2.@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@7R/8/6p1/2K2p2/5k2/7p/8/8 b - - 1 66@@EndFEN@@  66...Kg4  67.Kd4  g5  68.Kd3!  @@StartBracket@@not @@StartFEN@@7R/8/8/5pp1/3K2k1/7p/8/8 w - - 0 68@@EndFEN@@  68.Ke3  Kg3  69.Rh5  f4+  70.Ke2  g4  71.Kf1  Kh2  72.Rg5  g3  73.Rg8  g2+  74.Kf2  Kh1  75.Rg7  f3  76.Rg6  h2-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@7R/8/8/5pp1/6k1/3K3p/8/8 b - - 1 68@@EndFEN@@  68...Kg3  69.Rh5=   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@R7/P7/6p1/2K2p2/5k1p/1r5P/8/8 b - - 5 62@@EndFEN@@  62...Rb7  63.Kc6  Rf7  64.Kb6  g5  65.Rg8  Rxa7  66.Kxa7  g4-+  The pawns are too fast and the White king is very far away. }
57. Kg4
{ 57.Kg2  Kg5  58.a7  f5  59.Kg1  Ra2  60.Kh1  Kf4  61.Rg8  Rxa7  62.Rxg6  would have led to a draw. }
57... Ra4+ 58. Kf3 Kg5 59. a7 Ra1 60. Ke3 Ra3+ 61. Ke4 Ra2 62. Kf3 Ra6 63. Ke4
Ra3 64. Kd5 Kf4 65. Rh8 Rxa7 66. Rxh4+ Kf5 67. Rh8 Rd7+ 68. Kc5 g5 69. Rh6 Ke5
70. h4 gxh4 71. Rxh4 Rc7+ 72. Kb6 Rc2 73. Rh1 f5 74. Re1+ Kf4 75. Rf1+ Ke4 76.
Re1+ Kf3 77. Rf1+ Rf2 78. Rd1 f4 79. Kc5 Kg2 80. Kd4 f3 *

