[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Vladimir Kramnik vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Exercise #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r3q1k/R3nrb1/1p1p2b1/3Pp3/1PB1N1Q1/6PP/5PK1/4R3 w - - 0 28"]
[SetUp "1"]

28. Ng5
{ This position could have arisen after @@StartFEN@@1r1q1r1k/R3n1b1/1p1p2b1/3Pp1Q1/1PB1N3/6PP/5PK1/4R3 b - - 1 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Rf7  27.Qg4  Qf8  but I was worried about 28.Ng5. It turns out that it was a needless worry. What is the best move in this position? }
28... Rxf2+ 29. Kg1 Bh6 { This quiet move shuts down everything. } 30. Ne6 Qf6
{ Black's position is safe. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Vladimir Kramnik vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Exercise #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r4k/4qrb1/1p1p2Q1/3Pp3/1P2N3/5PPP/8/R5K1 w - - 0 32"]
[SetUp "1"]

32. Ng5
{ White's move is a bit too optimistic. How do you react to the threats? }
32... Kg8 33. Qh7+ Kf8 34. Ne6+ Ke8 { There is no checkmate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Vladimir Kramnik vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Exercise #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1k3/4qr2/1p1pNb2/3Pp2Q/1P6/5PPP/8/R5K1 w - - 0 36"]
[SetUp "1"]

36. g4 { White gave Black an opportunity to untangle his pieces. How? } 36...
Qb7
{ Black now uses the two pieces that are active to create checkmate threats before White can push the pawns far enough up the board. }
37. Rd1 { Or  37.g5  Qxd5-+  . } 37... Qa6
{ Now White's king is very vulnerable, while the black king is very safe with the bishop on f6 guarding all the key dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Vladimir Kramnik vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Exercise #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k1b/5r2/1p1p2Q1/3PpNP1/1q6/5P1P/2r5/3R2K1 w - - 0 44"]
[SetUp "1"]

44. Nd4 { Can you find the simplest and cleanest way to finish it off? } 44...
exd4 45. Qxc2 Qc3 46. Qe4 Qe3+ 47. Qxe3 dxe3
{ The endgame is of course winning for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Beating World Champions"]
[Black "Game 10: Vladimir Kramnik vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Dortmund 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ A shift from my previous games, as during the phase of 2009-2011 I had played 9...Ne8 almost exclusively. I cannot recall whether it was specifically because of the game we played in the Olympiad that I switched to Nh5, but I know there were problems in the Ne8 lines.  The game went  9...Ne8  10.Nd2  f5  11.c5  Nf6  12.a4!  @@StartBracket@@ Kramnik's improvement over my legendary games against Gelfand and Beliavsky in this line from 2009 and 2010@@EndBracket@@  12...f4  13.Nc4  g5  14.Ba3   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p1n2/2PPp1p1/PPN1Pp2/2N5/4BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nb5!  This important move is probably close to a clear refutation of the whole idea involving 12...f4. White is significantly better after 16.Bg4! However, it was not known at the time:   A@@EndBracket@@  14...Nxe4  15.f3  a6  16.Nxc7  Nc3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pN1n1bp/p2p4/2PPp1p1/PPN1np2/5P2/4B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Qxc7  17.fxe4+-  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pN1n1bp/p2p4/2PPp1p1/PPN2p2/2n2P2/4B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qe1  Nxe2+  18.Qxe2  Rb8  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pN1n1bp/p2p4/2PPp1p1/PPN2p2/5P2/4Q1PP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Qxc7  19.cxd6  Qd8  20.dxe7  Qxe7  21.d6  Qe6  22.Bb2  White is better as in Berkes-Nyzhnyk, Germany 2013  and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2q1bp/p7/3Pp1p1/PPN2p2/5P2/4Q1PP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Bb2±  is even an improvement  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/1pN1n1bp/p2p4/2PPp1p1/PPN2p2/5P2/4Q1PP/R1B2RK1 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.cxd6  Nf5  20.Ne6  Nd4  21.Qd3  Nxe6  22.dxe6  Bxe6  23.Bb2±  Once again, White has a stable advantage.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p1n2/1NPPp1p1/PPN1Pp2/8/4BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Ne8  15.Ba3  Ng6  16.Bg4±  .   Back to the Olympiad game against Kramnik. After 14.Ba3 it continued @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p1n2/2PPp1p1/PPN1Pp2/B1N5/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...g4  15.cxd6  cxd6  16.b5  Ne8  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2n1bp/3p1n2/1P1Pp3/P1N1Ppp1/B1N5/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...f3!  is the best move  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/pp2n1bp/3p4/1P1Pp3/P1N1Ppp1/B1N5/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bxg4  Qc7  18.Be2  f3  19.b6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b1nrk1/ppq1n1bp/3p4/1P1Pp3/P1N1P3/B1N2p2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.gxf3  Bh3  20.Kh1!  Bxf1  21.Bxf1  is a weird-looking positional sacrifice, but White is much better as Black doesn't have a real attack. That being said it is not very intuitive or human in any regard@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1b1nrk1/ppq1n1bp/1P1p4/3Pp3/P1N1P3/B1N2p2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...axb6  20.Nb5?  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@r1b1nrk1/1pq1n1bp/1p1p4/3Pp3/P1N1P3/B1N2p2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.gxf3  Bh3  21.Nb5  Qd8  22.Kh1  Bxf1  23.Bxf1  Rf6  24.Bh3+-  White is probably winning  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b1nrk1/1pq1n1bp/1p1p4/1N1Pp3/P1N1P3/B4p2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...fxe2  21.Qxe2  Qd8  22.Nbxd6  Nxd6  23.Bxd6  Rf7  24.Bxe5  Ng6⇆  Kramnik-Nakamura, Khanty Mansiysk Olympiad 2010. }
10. c5 Nf4 11. a4 f5 12. Bc4 fxe4 13. Nxe4 h6
{ A practical move to prevent a knight from going to g5/e6 and also potentially preparing a pawn push with g6-g5-g4. }
14. Re1 Bg4 15. Ra3
{ A common theme in the Bayonet variation of the Kings Indian when white pushes his pawn to a4. }
15... g5 16. h3
{ Not a bad move as Kramnik has a specific theme in mind, but it does give Black more targets potentially.  Oddly after  16.a5  Neg6  17.Bxf4  Nxf4  18.Bf1+-  the computer thinks White is close to winning here due to the huge positional space advantage on the queenside combined with the super powerful knight on e4. }
16... Bh5 17. Bxf4 Rxf4 18. g3 Rf8 19. a5
{ Similar to the line with 16.a5, except White has pushed the pawns to h3 and g3 which creates some weaknesses. }
19... Kh8 20. Kg2 Rb8
{ A waiting move. I am not really sure why I chose this move, but I suspect that I couldn't find a better way to sit on the position without making a concession. Here are some other moves:   20...Qd7?  21.Nxe5+-   20...Qe8  21.cxd6  cxd6  22.Nxd6  Qd7  23.Ne4±   20...Bg6  21.h4  g4  22.Nh2  h5  23.f3+-  . }
21. Qd2 b6 { Trying to rip open the queenside and use my rook on the b file. }
22. axb6 axb6 23. Nfxg5
{ An interesting sacrifice by Kramnik. In previous years, Kramnik almost certainly would not have gone for this idea, but for the last decade of his career, he became more optimistic about attacking and gaining the initiative. }
23... hxg5 24. Qxg5 Bg6
{ Better would have been  24...Rf5  25.Qh4  Bf6!  @@StartBracket@@a move that I completely missed during the game@@EndBracket@@  26.Nxf6  Ng6  27.Qxh5+  @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@1r1q3k/2p5/1p1p1Nn1/2PPpr1b/1PB4Q/R5PP/5PK1/4R3 w - - 1 27@@EndFEN@@  27.Qe4  Qxf6-+  Black's attack on the kingside is unstoppable  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1r1q3k/2p5/1p1p1Nn1/2PPpr1Q/1PB5/R5PP/5PK1/4R3 b - - 0 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Rxh5  28.Nxh5  Qg5  29.cxd6  cxd6  30.Be2  Qd2  31.Kf1  Rf8-+  and White has a rook and a bishop for the queen but is completely lost due to the lack of coordination of the pieces. }
25. cxd6 cxd6 26. Ra7 Rc8
{ Another mistake. Surprisingly, Black is much better after  26...Rf7  27.Qg4  Qf8  .  During the game I was extremely worried about Ng5, but as usual, computers show that the classic Nimzowitch saying 'The threat is stronger than the execution' is almost always true. After  28.Ng5  Rxf2+  29.Kg1  Bh6  @@StartBracket@@this quiet move shuts down everything@@EndBracket@@  30.Ne6  Qf6  Black has a significant advantage. }
27. Rxe7 Rxc4 28. f3 Rc2+ 29. Kg1 Rc8
{ Or  29...b5  30.h4  30...Rc8  31.h5  Re8  32.Qxg6  Rxe7  33.h6  Bxh6  34.Qxh6+  Rh7  35.Qxd6  Qxd6  36.Nxd6  Rc2=  . }
30. Ra1 Rf7 31. Qxg6 Qxe7 32. Ng5
{ Too optimistic. Better would have been  32.Nxd6  Rff8  33.Nxc8  Rxc8  .  Due to the lack of pawns on the board, this should be a draw despite Black having an extra bishop and a safer king. }
32... Kg8 33. Qh7+ Kf8 34. Ne6+ Ke8 { There is no checkmate! } 35. Qh5
{ If  35.Qg8+  then  35...Bf8  36.Qg4  Qb7  .   After the game, @@StartBracket@@this was the last round@@EndBracket@@ Kramnik and I ended up analyzing the position after  35.b5  for close to an hour. When all was said and done he concluded that it was the best move. We never reached a definite conclusion, but we both thought that Black should probably be winning:  35...Qf6  36.Rf1  Bh6  37.Qe4  Qf5-+  . }
35... Bf6
{ Another blunder that highlights just how hard it is to play some of these positions as a human. }
36. g4
{ The fact that the computer evaluates the position arising after  36.Qg6!  Qd7  37.g4=∞  as equal despite Black being up a rook, says a lot about how powerful the knight on e6 is, and how Black's pieces are not active at all. }
36... Qb7
{ Now Black can untangle and use the two pieces that are active to create checkmate threats before White can push the pawns far enough up the board. }
37. Rd1 { Or  37.g5  Qxd5-+  . } 37... Qa6
{ Now White's king is very vulnerable while the black king is very safe with the bishop on f6 guarding all the key dark squares. }
38. Qg6 Ke7 39. g5 Bh8
{ Now White has no checks and the game is objectively over. } 40. Re1 Qa3 41.
Nd4 Qxb4 42. Nf5+ { If  42.Qe6+  then  Kd8-+  . } 42... Kf8 43. Rd1
{ Or  43.Qxd6+  Qxd6  44.Nxd6  Rd8  45.Nxf7  Kxf7  46.Rb1  Kg6  47.Rxb6+  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@3r3b/8/1p4k1/3Pp1P1/8/5P1P/8/1R4K1 w - - 2 47@@EndFEN@@  47.h4  Kh5-+  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@3r3b/8/1R4k1/3Pp1P1/8/5P1P/8/6K1 b - - 0 47@@EndFEN@@  47...Kxg5  48.d6  Bf6!  . }
43... Rc2 44. Nd4 exd4 { The simplest and cleanest way to finish it off. } 45.
Qxc2 Qc3 46. Qe4 Qe3+ 47. Qxe3 dxe3 48. Kg2 Bc3 49. Kf1 Rxf3+ 50. Ke2 Rxh3 *

