[SetUp "1"]

34. Nf3
{ In this example from a bullet game Black played  34...Qe7  and missed his chance to gain a huge advantage. How? }
34... Nxf3 35. Qxf3 { Or  35.Kxf3  Qxh3  . } 35... Ne1+ 36. Rxe1 Qxe1
{ The material advantage is one thing - the airy white king another. White will not survive much longer. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Exercises"]
[Black "Ian Nepomniachtchi vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Online Blitz 2007"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r3k1/1p3pbp/3p4/q2Pn1p1/4P3/1B3p1P/P3NPP1/3QR1K1 w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

24. Nd4
{ The intention of the earlier ...f3 was to break up the kingside with ...fxg2 and that is indeed a great move in this position. However, Black found a more forcing continuation. Can you see it? }
24... Nd3
{ The knight can not be captured, as the rook would be hanging. From d3 it supports ...Rc1, breaks the communication between the white queen and knight and is looking forward to a great outpost on f4. }
25. Rf1
{ The game continued  25.Re3  Rc1  , sacrificing the queen for knight and rook.   25.Nf5  Nxe1  26.Ne7+  Kf8  27.Nxc8  fxg2  keeps the material balanced, but the g2 pawn will eventually win the game. }
25... fxg2 { Now this capture comes with an attack on the rook. } 26. Kxg2 Nf4+
27. Kh2 Rc3
{ With the double threat of  28.--  Rxh3  and  28.--  Rd3  forking the queen and knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
