[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Exercises"]
[Black "Evgeny Postny vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Online Blitz 2005"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rrk/ppp1q2p/3p3b/3Pp3/2Pn1pP1/2NQ3P/PPR2P1K/4NR2 w - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

27. Rd2 { White's position looks a little suspicious, don't you think? } 27...
f3
{ This attacks the rook, cuts the queen's line of sight to the kingside and clears the f4-square.  28.--  Bf4  29.Kg1  Qh4  is a threat now. }
28. Ne4
{ This is played to answer  28...Bf4  with  29.Ng3  , but even that would offer Black a winning attack. }
28... Bxd2
{ It is also possible to change the move order and start with 28...Rxg4. } 29.
Qxd2 Rxg4 30. hxg4
{ 30.Ng3  Rh4  simply leaves Black a pawn up with an ongoing attack on White's shattered kingside. }
30... Qh4+ 31. Kg1 Ne2+ { White has to sacrifice his queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Exercises"]
[Black "Jon Ludvig Hammer vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Baku 2016"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2r2kb/pq2p2p/1pnn1ppB/2p5/2P2QN1/5NP1/PP2PPKP/3RR3 w - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21. Kg1 { Find a way to improve the position and gain the initiative. } 21...
Nf7
{ 21...f5  right away is premature, as it allows White to plant a knight on e5 with  22.Nge5  .  It's better to prepare that move by controlling the e5-square. Meanwhile, there is nothing White can do to stop the pawn avalanche. }
22. h3 f5 23. Ngh2 e5 24. Qc1 e4
{ Black activated his bishop, gained space and seized control over the central dark squares for his knights. The game continued:  25.Nh4  Rxd1  26.Rxd1  Nd4  27.Re1  Qa6  with full pressure on White's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Exercises"]
[Black "Boris Gelfand vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Bursa 2010"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1bk1/1pp2r2/1p1P1n2/P3p2p/2N1Pp2/2N2Pp1/4B1nP/R2QR1BK w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

24. dxc7
{ White chose not to recapture the g2-knight right away and attack the black queen first. He probably still regrets that decision. }
24... Nxe1
{ Black has a zwischenzug of his own: He threatens a pretty mate with  26.--  g2  . }
25. Qxe1
{ Or  25.cxd8=Q  g2  as mentioned, so White removes the pesky knight, but Black played g2+ anyway. }
25... g2+
{ This lures the king out of his shelter, gaining tempi for the attack. } 26.
Kxg2 Rg7+ 27. Kh1 { 27.Kf2  Bc5+  28.Kf1  Bh3  or the other way around. } 27...
Bh3 { Every move comes with a deadly threat. This time it is 28...Bg2 . } 28.
Bf1
{ The only other way to defend g2 is  28.Qf2  , but  28...Qd4  29.Bf1  Qxf2  30.Bxf2  Bxf1  31.Rxf1  Rxc7  forces liquidation into a winning endgame. Don't forget that White already lost an exchange. }
28... Qd3 { Black mocks the overloaded bishop and threatens  29.--  Qxf3  . }
29. Nxe5
{ Or  29.Bxd3  Bg2  and @@StartFEN@@r4bk1/1pP3r1/1p3n2/P3p2p/2N1Pp2/2Nq1P1b/7P/R3QBBK w - - 5 29@@EndFEN@@  29.Bxh3  Qxf3+  30.Bg2  Qxg2  . }
29... Bxf1
{ Black can ignore the attack on his queen once again, due to the threat of  30.--  Bg2  . }
30. Qxf1 Qxc3 { The rest is a mop-up job. } 31. Rc1
{ After  31.Nd3  Qxc7  Black keeps his extra rook. } 31... Qxe5 32. c8=Q Rxc8
{ Being a piece down after  33.Rxc8  Qe6  Gelfand called it a day. } *

