25. Ne6
{ White had everything under control, but his last move was careless. Strike while you have the chance. }
25... Nf3+
{ White's knight move left f3 unprotected. The safest option was probably to control that square even better with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p2q2p/p2p3b/P2P4/1B1NPpnn/R2B4/5PP1/1Q3RK1 w - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Be2  , which would also have opened up the third rank for the rook. }
26. gxf3 { Or  26.Kh1  Qh4  . } 26... Qh4 27. fxg4
{ If  27.Re1  then  27...Qh2+  28.Kf1  Qxf2  . } 27... Qxg4+ 28. Kh2 Qh4+ 29.
Kg1 f3
{ 29...Qg4+  was the game continuation, with a repetition followed by a similar winning approach, but  29...f3  is cleaner. }
30. Rc1
{ White prepares the evacuation of his king in response to a check on the g-file. If the king arrives at e1, the bishop could block a check on the first rank. }
30... Rf4
{ 30...Kf7  preparing ...Rg8 is the right idea, but the wrong execution. After  31.Rc7+  White's control over g7 would complicate matters. In fact, Black is much worse here. }
31. Nxf4
{ 31.Bxd6  Rg4+  32.Bg3  Rxg3+  33.fxg3  Be3+  34.Kf1  Qh1  also leads to a mate. }
31... Bxf4
{ Now  32.--  Qh2  33.Kf1  Qh1  can only be postponed for a move by a spite check on c8. }
