18... Nh7 { With the double threat of both ...Nxg5 as well as ...Bd4. } 19. Na4
{ Seting a trap.   19.Bc1  Bd4-+  followed in the game. } 19... Qxa5
{ The strongest move. Black does not only collect the pawn, but also breaks White's restriction on the queenside.   The materialistic approach with  19...Qa7?  is way too passive due to  20.Bf4!  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@  20...Bd4?!  wins the exchange, but suddenly it is Black who is stuck with horrible pieces. After  21.Nb6!  @@StartBracket@@  a very unpleasant move to face; Black cannot take both on f2 and b6  @@EndBracket@@  21...Bxb6  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/qp3p1n/pN1p2p1/P2P3p/2pbPB2/1n3PN1/RP2BRPP/3Q2K1 b - - 7 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Bxf2+  22.Kxf2+-  when Black is up the exchange, but very few of his pieces can move and d6 and c4 are also about to drop  22...Rd8  23.Be3!  and some discoveries are coming  @@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/qp3p1n/pb1p2p1/P2P3p/2p1PB2/1n3PN1/RP2BRPP/3Q2K1 w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.axb6  Qxb6  23.Bxc4+-  the material is even, but Black has lost all coordination and his great dark-squared bishop.   B@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/qp3pbn/p2p2p1/P2P3p/N1p1PB2/1n3PN1/RP2BRPP/3Q2K1 b - - 5 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nxa5!  Taking the pawn now is still the best strategy, but with the queen on a7 this is a much better version for White compared to the previous move. After  21.Bxd6  White at least has chances in this messy position. }
20. Be3 b5
{ A great multi-purpose move. Black stops Nb6, protects his pawn on c4 and simply expands on the queenside. Black's queenside majority gives him a decisive advantage. }
